AGI - It was a complicated day for TikTok > which first suspended &nbsp; "voluntarily" the new Lite> function ended under accusation in Europe and then saw the threat of banning in the United States converted into law". These are two events that have no connection between them, but which address different types of problems posed by the spread of the very popular video platform. The Lite version rewards users for the time spent in front of the screens and, according to the EU, ends up creating dependence. "Our children are not guinea pigs for social networks", commented the European commissioner at Digital, Thierry Breton>, who on Monday announced the opening of an investigation by Brussels and threatened its suspension from tomorrow.
&nbsp;
TikTok Lite is based on the "watch-and-get-rewarded" system, that is, look and get rewarded. It is a strategy designed to push people to stay longer on the platform and open it more often. It is the same system used in online gaming, creating expectation for rewards, as it was a video game.<br> Assign to each user of the tasks, how to watch certain videos, put like, follow influencers or invite other friends on the platform. Who completes them is rewarded with points, which can be exchanged in turn to receive prizes, such as Amazon vouchers, gift cards via PayPal or the internal virtual currency in TikTok, usable only for purchases on the app. A practice that according to the Commission "creates dependence" and poses a risk, especially for children. Brussels accuses TikTok, owned by the Chinese company ByteDance, of launching its Lite version before publishing the report on possible risks that could cause users required by the new Digital Service Act of the European Union.
&nbsp;
Taking note of this decision by TikTok, he stated that "it always tries to work constructively with the European Commission and other regulators" and announced the suspension of the system to awards "while it addresses the concerns that have been raised".&nbsp; The social network had repeatedly remembered that only 18 years of age could participate and that applied procedures to ensure the age of users - such as the need to take a selfie with an identity document, or give credit card authorization - but for experts it is easily deceived systems. “I welcome TikTok’s voluntary suspension of the ‘premium’ feature,” the French secretary of state reacted to digital affairs, Marina Ferrari, underlining that he “ warned, since its launch, about this questionable comes and about the risks it entailed to its users. France was, along with Spain, the country 'test' of TikTok Lite. TikTok, who has attracted more than 1.5 billion users worldwide, has been accused for several years in the United States and Europe of causing addiction among teenagers. The Chinese platform was already under investigation by the Commission, open in February, for alleged shortcomings in the protection of minors under the DSA.
&nbsp;
TikTok is under pressure even beyond the Atlantic. The help package that Joe Biden has turned into law also provides for the ban on the app from online stores in the United States unless the company is sold by breaking all links with the Chinese mother house ByteDance. "This unconstitutional law forbids TikTok and we will challenge it in court," says CEO Shou Zi Chew>, a syngaporian entrepreneur in a video published on the platform, "We believe that the facts and the law are clearly on our side and that we will eventually prevail."
&nbsp;
The U.S. government is especially concerned about the fate of data collected in the United States that, it claims, could be transferred to Beijing. "The fact is that we invested billions of dollars to keep US data safe and our platform free from external influences and manipulations," adds Shou "This ban would have to be 7 million companies and would silence 170 million Americans. We will continue to invest and innovate to ensure that TikTok remains a space where Americans of every social class can come to share their experiences, find joy and be inspired."

