AGI - Palestinian director Rashid Masharawi wants to "export a different film image of Gaza", now devastated by the war, while he presides over the jury of the eighth International Women's Film Festival in Aswan, dedicated to the "cinema of resistance". In the background of the war in the Strip, it was decided to project during the event six Palestinian short films in the contest that brings together directors of the whole region. All this despite many voices in the Arab world had asked for the suspension of all artistic and cultural activities in solidarity with the gazebos. Masharawi is internationally known for being the first Palestinian director to participate in the official selection of the Cannes Film Festival, with his film "Haifa", in 1996. Born in the Gaza Strip by refugees from the port city of Jaffa, the director now lives in Ramallah, in the occupied West Bank. He stated that "do not consider art and cinema as pure entertainment". Adding: "If film festivals do not play their role when large disasters occur, such as what is happening in Palestine, then why do they exist?"
&nbsp;
Among the six Palestinian films present in Aswan is the 14-minute documentary "Threads of Silk" by filmmaker Wala Saadah, who was killed last month in the war. The film analyzes the meaning of embroidery on the Palestinian robe "thawb". "I am from Palestine", written and shot by director Iman al-Dhawahari, tells instead of a Palestinian-American girl who, in an American school, is shocked to see a map of the world without her country. The 16-minute documentary "A Cut Off Future", by Alia Ardoghli, highlights the daily experiences of 27 girls between 11 and 17 years in the shadow of Israeli occupation.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In his last film, whose work is underway, Masharawi said he wanted to denounce what he called "the lie of self-defense". "The occupation of Israel has blown up the study of an artist in Gaza with paintings and statues. Where is self-defense when killing artists and intellectuals calling terrorists?", said the 62-year-old at AFP.&nbsp;
Two months after the war began, Masharawi started a new project: a support fund for the cinema in the besieged strip. The "Films from Distance Zero" initiative supports Gazani directors who live "under bombings or have become refugees" to produce their films. Several women directors are active in the project, about which Masharawi said: "Always in the most difficult times, we find Palestinian women on the front line."
&nbsp;
Gaza theaters were closed at the end of the 1980s during the Palestinian revolt against Israel known as the First Intifada, but were reopened after the creation of the Palestinian Authority in the 1990s.&nbsp; Hamas' control changed all this: The Islamist political movement considers cinema as "contrary" to the values of Islam.
However, last year an outdoor film festival was held, "taking into account the customs and traditions of the territory", said at the time a Hamas official. For Masharawi, now more than ever, it is necessary to support the cinema and to ensure that "a different film image of Gaza" reaches the world > to "make the truth prevail in front of the lies of the Israeli occupation". At the center of Masharawi's work there is identity. "It is difficult (for Israel) to occupy our memories, our identities, our music, our history and our culture," he said.&nbsp; Israel "is losing a lot of time in a project destined for failure and that will kill many of us," he said, referring to the war in Gaza.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Masharawi said that the Arab public's solidarity with the Palestinian people, "and I mean the people and not their leadership," may result "from their impotence and the restrictions of their systems (of government)". He added: "I used to dream that Arab governments were like their people, but I say clearly: This did not happen, even after we touched the 200 days of war."
&nbsp;
